segments.text: South Vietnam can shove the United States around for 10 years?
They don't have a military that amounts to a hill of beans.
North Vietnam doesn't either.
Who fed North Vietnam on these people?
China?
But we wouldn't dare go to North Vietnam or beyond a certain level here.
We wouldn't bring China into it.
We would not bring China into it.
China was in it.
The reason people protested is because they were frustrated and angry and not just a little put out that they lost their sons or whatever.
I believe that a lot of those people who protested why I hated it at the time and why that kind of thing grates on any military man.
I understand at least why they did it.
And I suppose there were probably a lot of military people the last two or three years of that war wanted to march because of the stupidity.
the way we approached it, because of the cost that we laid down for it.
And we still ended up with a fistful of nothing.
And all we got out of Vietnam was a bunch of dead soldiers and a black wall.
And that's a price that stinks.
You were talking about the military.
The command was thinking of, what do you think of the fact that when they were first going in, that initially the CIA and the military were completely opposed to it.
They said there was no way to either win or there was no strategic objectives in that particular theater.
It wasn't that important.
It wasn't worth the effort.
It was about 63, 64 when they were talking about it.
Then at 65, when the Marines landed with 50,000 men, they were told at that time, you know, they weren't told.
What they said was, I'm not too certain exactly what our objective is.
But what they thought was, we'll go in there with 50,000 and scare the snot out of these people.
We're going to get a lot of this nonsense stopped just by our sheer numbers.
the military mindset of an Oriental, they don't care if they fight 5,000 or five.
They are a unique critter.
And that's the hardest thing for Americans to go against.
That's the reason we had so much trouble in the Second World War with Japs.
We couldn't imagine the things that they would live through.
We could not fathom the things those people would, you know, the lengths they would go to.
They would live worse than animals.
And they would fight and die for old mother country.
See, that's a mindset completely different than America.
We don't want to die for old mother country.
We want to live for it.
Matter of fact, Patton even said it.
He said, Patton, you're not a hero because you go out there and die for your country.
You make that other son of a bitch die for his country.
That was Patton's words.
You want to go out there and make him die for his country, make a hero out of him.
We just, boy, we have the hardest time with an oriental mind
And we assume certain things about them.
It's not true.
We create a lot of problems for ourselves.
I don't know how many people, if you saw ten Orientals walking down the street, your natural conditioning after what you've seen in the movies and all is that at least nine of them know karate.
When all they are really maybe is Nikon salesmen.
But we assume certain things, and we act a certain way because of that assumption.
Same things happen in the Japanese, and same things happen in Vietnam, Korea.
We think we're going to do a certain thing, and we don't do it.
And the worst part of that is the politicians are doing a lot of the assuming.
We have people...
in very strong, powerful positions that don't have the foggiest notion of the people they're dealing with.
And yet, they're gonna carry out policies that they don't even understand.
So, it was bad intelligence or just not listening to the intelligence?
I think it was a lack of intelligence.
lack of intelligence people than a lot of our politicians that are elected people.
For instance, we elect somebody from Texas to go represent us in Washington.
Now the person that we know of here in Texas that we elect, do you elect that man based on his military background?
Do you elect him on the basis of how successful he is in business?
Do you elect him on
the basis of how charismatic he is?
Do we elect him?
We just go through his college background, his educational background.
Do we do it on that?
Almost every one of those with the exception of the military bid.
We don't care about that.
We're going to do it more on his charismatic comportment and his ability to function as a businessman.
more rapidly than any other thing.
Isn't that about right?
Now we're going to send him to Washington and he's going to sit up there and deal in all these things around the world.
We had a political pot full of them up there in Washington all during those ten years of Vietnam.
How many of those people had one iota
of military background.
Now, this is what I'm talking about, the lack of intelligence.
If I said to you, Benny, I've got a little project I need blown up.
Now, if your expertise doesn't happen to be in explosives, I'm just going to hand you the caps and the charges
and I'm going to tell you where I want it, I want this thing blown out of there, and you go out there and take care of it.
Would you go do that?
I'm sure I'd think about it, yeah.
You'd think about it, because I told you and I was your superior, and you'd think about going and doing it.
But you'd also have enough common sense to say, wait a minute, tell me something about this.
What makes this go off?
If you didn't know, you'd be pretty stupid not to ask.
But what if you went next door and asked my neighbor?
And he happened to know all about electronics and absolutely nothing about explosives.
But he told you what he thought.
And based on what he told you to do and the fact that I gave you the direction, you went out there to do it.
And you not only blew that thing out of there, but yourself and a bunch of neighbors with it.
Now,
I'm the one who gave the direction.
Do they come to me and say, why did you tell that boy and not know that he'd know how to do it?
Well, it's not my fault.
That guy told him how to do it.
Now, he goes to jail, and I'm still sitting in my office.
That's what happens in Washington quite often.
We have people who will ask other people
who have about the same amount of experience maybe in a given area that they do.
How many politicians do you suppose were in politics to escape going to Vietnam?
I just, I guess my frustration is that I know
of so many of the different senators that would stand up and say things about the war that they had no experience to understand what was going on.
Yet Senator Iannui, who knew what it was to fight a war and lost an arm and so on, he would say certain things
And they'd ignore him.
And I'm not just saying him, but many like him.
It's the guys who have the voice of experience in that given area that were saying things that they should have listened to.
Whether we agree with what they were saying or not.
We ought to know where they're coming from to say such a thing.
But see, if I say something that you disagree with,
If you don't talk to me about it and find out why I say that, you're not going to understand.
You'll just sit there and disagree.
And we'll never reach that point where we have this understanding.
And if we don't understand, there's not much grounds for appreciation either.
Respect.
And I have very little respect
for some of them.
Because there were a number that backed Jane Fonda doing what she did.
That's a dangerous game.
I knew it.
He said some things that I disagree with.
But at least I understand part of what he's saying.
And in order for me to understand all of what he's saying, I'd have to sit down and talk to him.
But quite often, when a direction's given, the guy who gives the direction doesn't give the instruction.
And he insulates himself with neighbors and other people, other than soldiers, to take the heat when things blow up in his face.
And they're the connivers that are just frosted.
And how much of that was responsible for all that went on in Vietnam, God only knows.
But entirely too much.
You've always got people who are concerned about being re-elected.
And they'll do and say anything to be re-elected.
And they're the ones I have no respect for.
Regardless of why Lyndon Johnson, whatever motivated him,
There's a raft of reasons, but part of the reason, Lyndon Johnson didn't run again.
Because of Vietnam.
So, I take my hat off to a man that at least says, I cannot stomach this any longer.
And walked away.
Then those that'll sit there and run and lie and do whatever...
the common soldier.
It was like when you were there.
You did what you were told to do.
But the reason the common soldier, even in Nazi Germany, the reason the common soldier continued to fight and die is because he had a certain faith in the command.
That faith in our command started to deteriorate in the mid to late 60s.
And by 70,
And on.
It was shot.
Nobody trusted him.
How would you like to have been there then?
Not after Tet.
After, well, during Vietnamization, I wouldn't have wanted to have been there.
Because then everybody, they were pulling troops out.
They're still fighting, and then you're just going to die for absolutely nothing.
You've got people, the next unit's being pulled back to the States, and you're still there having a fight.
And you're dying.
See, you're almost in a position where it's a dying situation.
At least if you think you're dying for something.
During the Second World War, our guys were dying, but they knew what they were dying for.
And that was the frustrating factor of Vietnam.
We were, you know, they were never told.
I mean, our own government never said we had a specific direction.
What are we trying to do?
So the guys get the feeling that they're literally in a dying situation and have no knowledge why their life is required.
You feel like the government leadership in general just betrayed the soldiers?

knowingly betrayed their trust yeah i do because i think too many people got involved in a situation where it was face saving time and they would rather save face than admit their error and cancel it save at least some lives because you know ultimately that's exactly what happened everybody kept
rattling and shaking until it finally got to the point it was obvious that we didn't have the facility for continuing it, much less the heart for it, and we were beat.
So we withdrew, and we left those people, and part of them were clamoring for that freedom, and they got it.
Now, the thing that happened was the exact thing that people like Jane Fonda clamored for.
Get out and let them run their own business.
That's their business.
Let them do it.
That's what they want to do.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
So we did.
And millions died.
Millions died.
That country was raped.
And Cambodia, which we were forbidden to go across these sacred borders, they were raped.
They got what they asked for.
But we picked up part of the ticket.
And our psyche continues to pay for it as a country.
People scream about, we shouldn't do this, we shouldn't do that.
What are they attached to it every time?
Like Vietnam.
Now you tell me.
We're not navel-gazing.
We don't look at the world anymore with a view towards accomplishing anything.
What we look at it, it seems to me now, is with an eye that we never want to be put in that position again.
So you feel the Vietnam syndrome is affecting foreign policy?
Oh, absolutely.
Just like Watergate Center.
That thing continues to affect everything.
I mean, everything we do now has got to have this grand investigation attached to it.
Everything.
Oh, man.
Of course, we're all...
I think you unplugged the lamp.
Unplug that other thing.
No.
Pause.
Well, you know...
I think we have a lot of good people in politics.
we get into a fighting situation.
I would certainly like to know that whoever, I'd like to know whoever's doing the directing has something specific in mind.
And I'll give you a case in point of the futility of the Bay of Pigs.
That thing was ramshackle from the beginning to its disastrous end.
And Vietnam is a reflection of that same thing.
And we went through three presidents during that fiasco.
And not one of them seemed to have any better grasp than the other.
It was like a booger on the finger.
You just sit there and keep flicking it, and that sucker won't come off.
And not one of them said, come here, General, and wipe it on his chest along with all of his other confetti.
You know, they didn't do that.
Now I want somebody, a president or whoever it is, to have the coyotes to stand up and say, this stinks, get out.
We just keep dancing.
Everybody wants to be re-elected.
That's what stinks about politics.
Your life is insignificant in light of my importance in Washington.
Bullshit.
The day will come when you'll have your sons.
How are you going to feel when they're called to go down to the canal to fight?
Because just as sure as God made politics and countries, there's going to be a conflict down there.
I'd certainly like to know that the one that's in charge has the brass of Harry Truman to stand up and say, we're going to do it, and we're going to do it to end it.
The way the world is today, the thing that they could do to affect it more than anything else
and understand who Jesus Christ is.
Stop thinking about fighting.
Start thinking about living.
The lethal potential is phenomenal.
It's just phenomenal.
We just keep flirting with it.
be nice.
My kids' kids could grow up and accomplish all God has intended.
That you and your children could grow up being able to travel anywhere in the world and know that God's in charge of you instead of someone else.
It's probably going to do it.
